────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. OVERVIEW & BIG PICTURE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The system performs CO-PO mapping in TWO independent layers:

  LAYER 1 — CO-PO Articulation Matrix (Primary)
    → Pure LLM semantic reasoning
    → Each (CO, PO) cell gets a STRENGTH value: 0, 1, 2, or 3
    → Done by: POMapperAgent  (agents/po_mapper.py)

  LAYER 2 — PI Alignment Matrix (Supporting / Accreditation)
    → LLM reads syllabus + CO statements + PI definitions
    → Each (CO, PI) cell is either MAPPED ("Y") or UNMAPPED ("N")
    → Done by: PIMapperAgent  (agents/pi_mapper.py)
    → PI mappings can OPTIONALLY recalculate CO-PO strengths
      (function: calculate_po_co_strengths)

These two layers are INDEPENDENT. Changes to the PI matrix do not automatically
overwrite the CO-PO Articulation Matrix unless you explicitly trigger a
recalculation (done from the frontend SubjectWorkspace page).

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2. KEY TERMINOLOGY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CO   — Course Outcome
         A specific, measurable learning result for a subject.
         Example: "CO1: Apply normalization techniques to design a relational schema"
         Bloom's Level: 3 (Apply) to 6 (Create) — L1 and L2 are NOT allowed.

  PO   — Program Outcome
         A broad graduate-level capability that the entire program achieves.
         PO1 to PO12 are the standard NBA program outcomes.
         Example: "PO1: Engineering Knowledge"

  PI   — Performance Indicator
         A fine-grained, measurable competency UNDER a PO.
         Each PO has 2–4 PIs. PI IDs follow the format: {po_num}.{competency}.{indicator}
         Example PI ID: "1.1.1" (under PO1, Competency 1.1, Indicator 1)
         Example PI: "Apply mathematical concepts like calculus to engineering problems."

  Strength — The CO-PO mapping intensity:
         0 = No relationship
         1 = Slight / Low
         2 = Moderate / Medium
         3 = Strong / High (NBA requirement for PO1, PO2, PO3)

  Bloom's Level — Cognitive complexity of a CO:
         L3 = Apply   (apply, implement, solve, use)
         L4 = Analyze (analyze, differentiate, compare, examine)
         L5 = Evaluate(evaluate, justify, assess, critique)
         L6 = Create  (design, create, formulate, develop, build)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3. DATA MODELS (SCHEMAS)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Defined in: core/schemas.py

  CourseOutcome
  ┌─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Field               │ Description                                       │
  ├─────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ co_id               │ "CO1", "CO2", etc.                                │
  │ statement           │ Full CO text starting with a Bloom's verb         │
  │ blooms_level        │ Integer 3–6                                       │
  │ blooms_keyword      │ "Apply", "Analyze", "Evaluate", "Create"          │
  │ confidence_score    │ Float 0.0–1.0 (LLM self-confidence)               │
  │ validation_status   │ "pending" | "approved" | "rejected"               │
  │ rejection_reason    │ Why the CO was flagged (optional)                 │
  └─────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  ProgramOutcome
  ┌─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ po_id               │ "PO1" to "PO12"                                   │
  │ statement           │ Standard NBA PO description                       │
  └─────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  MappingEntry  (CO-PO Articulation Matrix cell)
  ┌─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ co_id               │ CO identifier                                     │
  │ po_id               │ PO identifier                                     │
  │ strength            │ 0, 1, 2, or 3                                     │
  │ reasoning           │ Why this strength was assigned (AI text)          │
  │ confidence          │ Float 0.0–1.0                                     │
  │ validated           │ Boolean — whether it passed validation            │
  └─────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  PerformanceIndicator
  ┌─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ po_id               │ Parent PO (e.g. "PO1")                            │
  │ competency_id       │ Group ID (e.g. "1.1")                             │
  │ competency_statement│ Description of the competency group               │
  │ pi_id               │ Unique PI ID (e.g. "1.1.1")                       │
  │ pi_statement        │ Measurable competency description                 │
  └─────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  PIMappingEntry  (PI Alignment Matrix cell)
  ┌─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ co_id               │ CO identifier                                     │
  │ pi_id               │ PI identifier                                     │
  │ mapped              │ "Y" (aligned) or "N" (not aligned)                │
  │ reasoning           │ One-sentence explanation of why it is aligned     │
  │ suggestion          │ How to create alignment if currently "N"          │
  └─────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
4. PHASE 1 — COURSE OUTCOMES (CO) GENERATION
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Agent:   agents/co_generator.py
Trigger: Frontend "Course Outcomes" page → "Trigger CO Generator Agent" button

HOW IT WORKS:
  1. The system reads the uploaded syllabus (up to 4000 characters).
  2. It sends the syllabus + subject name to the LLM (temperature=0 for
     deterministic output).
  3. The LLM returns a JSON array of COs following these rules:
       - Bloom's Level MINIMUM is L3 (Apply)
       - L1 and L2 are strictly forbidden
       - Distribution across L3, L4, L5, L6
       - Every CO must start with an allowed Bloom's action verb
       - COs must be non-overlapping, measurable, practical
  4. COs are then validated by COValidatorAgent (agents/co_validator.py):
       - Checks for duplicate verbs
       - Checks Bloom's level distribution
       - Checks minimum word count
       - Up to 3 automatic retries if validation fails
  5. Human-in-the-loop: The user can provide critique feedback
     ("too theoretical", "missing design problems", etc.) and the agent
     regenerates the COs incorporating that feedback.

BLOOMS VERB RULES:
  L3 – Apply:    apply, demonstrate, implement, solve, use, execute, perform
  L4 – Analyze:  analyze, differentiate, compare, examine, break down, categorize
  L5 – Evaluate: evaluate, justify, assess, critique, defend, argue
  L6 – Create:   design, create, formulate, develop, construct, build, produce

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5. PHASE 2 — PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (PI) GENERATION
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Agent:   agents/pi_generator.py
Trigger: "Course Setup" page → Department & Vision Mission submission

HOW IT WORKS:
  1. The system loads a TEMPLATE of default PIs for the selected department
     from: core/default_pis.py

  2. The template covers PO1 through PO12, each with 2–4 PIs.
     Total typical PIs: ~26 entries.

  3. If the user provided a Vision & Mission text/PDF:
       → The LLM customizes the competency_statement and pi_statement to
         reflect the department's specific focus (e.g., software architectures
         for Computer Engineering, neural networks for AIML, etc.)
       → Same IDs (po_id, competency_id, pi_id) are KEPT — only the text changes.

  4. If no Vision & Mission was provided:
       → Default template PIs are used directly (no LLM call).

DEPARTMENT-SPECIFIC CUSTOMIZATIONS (from default_pis.py):
  • Computer Engineering  → PI 1.4.1: Computer architecture, OS, discrete math
                            PI 3.1.1: Software architectures, DB schemas, networking
  • Data Science          → PI 1.4.1: Statistics, data structures, databases
                            PI 3.1.1: Data pipelines, analytics dashboards
  • AIML                  → PI 1.4.1: Linear algebra, probability, optimization
                            PI 3.1.1: Neural networks, NLP, computer vision
  • Software Engineering  → Design patterns, secure software, OOP paradigms
  • Information Technology→ Cloud computing, network protocols, web tech
  • Mechanical Engineering→ Thermodynamics, fluid mechanics, materials science
  • Chemical Engineering  → Transport phenomena, reaction kinetics
  • Civil Engineering     → Structural analysis, soil mechanics, hydraulics

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6. PHASE 3 — CO-PO ARTICULATION MATRIX (AI MAPPING — LAYER 1)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Agent:   agents/po_mapper.py
File:    agents/po_mapper.py
Trigger: Frontend "Mapping" page → "Generate with AI" button
         (available ONLY if no mapping exists yet — one-time only)

HOW IT WORKS:
  1. The agent reads all generated COs as text:
       "CO1: Apply normalization techniques..."
       "CO2: Design a distributed database system..."
       ...

  2. The agent reads all 12 standard Program Outcomes (PO1–PO12) as text:
       "PO1: Engineering Knowledge — Apply..."
       "PO2: Problem Analysis — Identify and formulate..."
       ...

  3. A detailed prompt is sent to the LLM with STRICT RULES:
       - Strength 0: No meaningful relationship
       - Strength 1: Weak relationship
       - Strength 2: Moderate relationship
       - Strength 3: Strong relationship
       - PO1, PO2, PO3 MUST receive strong mappings (NBA requirement)
       - At least 2 strong mappings for major POs
       - Avoid random/meaningless mappings
       - Every cell includes a "reasoning" explanation

  4. The LLM returns a JSON array of MappingEntry objects covering
     every (CO, PO) combination.

  5. Results are saved to state.co_po_mapping and stored in the database.

  6. Validation runs (MappingValidatorAgent) — see Phase 5.

EXAMPLE OUTPUT (one entry in the JSON array):
  {
    "co_id": "CO1",
    "po_id": "PO1",
    "strength": 3,
    "reasoning": "CO1 directly applies mathematical models in database
                  normalization, fulfilling PO1 Engineering Knowledge.",
    "confidence": 0.91
  }

WHAT HAPPENS IN THE FRONTEND:
  - The matrix is rendered as a grid (COs as rows, POs as columns).
  - Each cell shows the strength: 3 (green), 2 (amber), 1 (rose), − (none)
  - Clicking a cell opens a popup showing:
       • The full CO statement
       • The full PO statement
       • The AI reasoning text
       • Bloom's taxonomy alignment explanation
       • A manual strength selector (0, 1, 2, 3) for override

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
7. PHASE 4 — PI ALIGNMENT MATRIX (AI MAPPING — LAYER 2)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Agent:   agents/pi_mapper.py → function run()
Trigger: Frontend "Mapping" page → "Auto-Map with AI" button (one-time only)

HOW IT WORKS:
  Step A — Initialize ALL combinations as UNMAPPED:
    For every CO × every PI combination, create a PIMappingEntry with:
      mapped = "N"
      reasoning = "No direct alignment found."
      suggestion = "Incorporate activities testing this PI."

    Example: 6 COs × 26 PIs = 156 total cells, all starting as "N".

  Step B — LLM identifies MAPPED combinations:
    The prompt includes:
      1. First 3000 characters of the syllabus text
      2. All CO statements (JSON)
      3. All PI statements (JSON)

    The LLM is asked:
      "Identify all (CO, PI) pairs that have a valid correlation.
       Correlation exists if the syllabus topic, when associated with
       the learning outcome, directly addresses the competency in the PI."

    The LLM returns ONLY the mapped "Y" pairs (not the unmapped ones).
    Each returned entry has:
      { "co_id": "CO1", "pi_id": "1.1.1", "reasoning": "..." }

  Step C — Update the matrix:
    For each LLM-returned pair, the system finds the corresponding entry
    in all_mappings and sets:
      mapped = "Y"
      reasoning = <LLM reasoning>
      suggestion = ""  (cleared since it's now mapped)

  Step D — Save:
    state.pi_mappings = list of all 156 PIMappingEntry objects
    (some "Y", most "N")

  IMPORTANT: The CO-PO Articulation Matrix (Layer 1) is NOT touched here.
  The PI matrix is a separate accreditation support tool.

WHAT HAPPENS IN THE FRONTEND:
  - The PI matrix is shown grouped by PO (PO1 → PO12), each PO row
    expandable to show its PIs.
  - Each cell shows "Y" (green) or "N" (grey).
  - Clicking a cell shows:
       • The CO statement
       • The PI full statement
       • Toggle button (Y ↔ N) for manual override
       • AI reasoning (if mapped)
       • "Ask AI How to Map This PI" button (for unmapped cells)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
8. PHASE 5 — MAPPING VALIDATION
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Agent:   agents/mapping_validator.py
Runs:    Automatically after CO-PO generation (no LLM needed — rule-based)

VALIDATION RULES:

  Rule 1: Every CO must map to at least one PO with strength >= 2
    → If any CO has NO moderate/strong mapping, it is flagged.
    → Issue example: "CO3 has no strong mapping (>=2) to any PO"

  Rule 2: PO1, PO2, and PO3 must have at least one CO mapping with strength >= 2
    → These are MANDATORY NBA requirements for accreditation.
    → Issue example: "PO2 has no strong CO mappings — NBA requirement not met"
    → Suggestion: "Ensure at least 2 COs map strongly to PO2"

  Rule 3: Low-confidence flag
    → Any mapping with confidence < 0.5 AND strength > 0 is flagged.
    → Issue example: "3 mappings have low confidence scores"

  RESULT:
    passed = True  → All rules satisfied
    passed = False → Issues list is returned for display + potential retry

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
9. STRENGTH CALCULATION LOGIC (PI → CO-PO)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Function: calculate_po_co_strengths() in agents/pi_mapper.py
Purpose:  Derive CO-PO strengths FROM the PI alignment matrix
          (This is an ALTERNATIVE to the LLM-based direct mapping)

ALGORITHM (per CO, per PO):
  1. Find all PIs that belong to this PO (po_pis)
  2. Count how many of those PIs have mapped = "Y" for this CO (mapped_count)
  3. Calculate percentage = (mapped_count / total_pis) * 100

  STRENGTH THRESHOLDS (NBA-calibrated for 3–4 PIs per PO):
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────┐
  │ Condition                                   │ Strength                 │
  ├─────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────┤
  │ mapped_count == 0                           │ 0 (No mapping)           │
  │ mapped_count >= total_pis OR percentage >= 40% │ 3 (Strong)           │
  │ percentage >= 20%                           │ 2 (Moderate)             │
  │ At least 1 PI mapped, but < 20%             │ 1 (Slight)               │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────┘

  NOTE: The old 67% threshold was too strict (required 3/4 PIs = nearly
  impossible for a single subject). The 40% threshold is the current
  calibrated standard.

EXAMPLE:
  PO1 has 4 PIs. CO1 is mapped to 2 of those PIs.
  percentage = (2/4) * 100 = 50%
  50% >= 40% → Strength = 3 (Strong)

  Reasoning stored: "CO1 maps to PO1 (Strength: 3) by aligning with
  2/4 performance indicators: 1.1.1, 1.3.1."

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
10. MANUAL OVERRIDE (HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

After the initial AI mapping, ALL changes must be done manually.
There is no "Re-Map" button — AI runs only ONCE per subject.

CO-PO MATRIX — Manual Override:
  • Click any cell in the Articulation Matrix.
  • A popup opens showing the AI reasoning and Bloom's alignment.
  • Use the strength selector (−, 1, 2, 3) to change the value.
  • Click "Save Matrix" to persist changes to the database.
  • You can also use "Ask AI How to Map This" for guidance on zero-strength cells.

PI ALIGNMENT MATRIX — Manual Override:
  • Click any cell in the PI Matrix.
  • Toggle the cell between "Y" (Mapped) and "N" (Unmapped).
  • The system updates the local state immediately.
  • Click "Save PI Matrix" to persist all changes.
  • You can ask AI for suggestions on unmapped cells without triggering a remap.

CO OUTCOMES — Manual Edit:
  • On the Course Outcomes page, click the edit icon on any CO.
  • Modify the statement text, Bloom's level, or keyword.
  • Click "Apply Changes" to update locally.
  • Click "Save Edits" to persist.
  • Click "Refine Outcomes" with feedback text to trigger a NEW AI regeneration
    (this ONLY applies to CO generation, not mapping).

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
11. RULE: AI MAPPING IS ONE-TIME ONLY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

By design, the AI mapping is performed only ONCE per subject:

  CO-PO Matrix:
    → "Generate with AI" button is shown ONLY when localMappings.length === 0
    → Once generated and saved, the button disappears permanently.
    → All future changes are manual (cell-by-cell strength editing).

  PI Matrix:
    → "Auto-Map with AI" button is shown ONLY when no PI has mapped = "Y"
    → Once generated and saved, the button disappears permanently.
    → All future changes are manual (Y/N toggling per cell).

WHY?
  This ensures that faculty manually review and own the mapping decisions.
  It prevents accidental AI overwriting of carefully adjusted accreditation
  matrices. NBA/NAAC accreditation requires faculty accountability for mappings.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
12. FILES & AGENTS INVOLVED
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Backend (Python):
  agents/po_mapper.py         — CO-PO LLM mapping agent (Layer 1)
  agents/pi_mapper.py         — CO-PI LLM mapping agent + strength calculator
  agents/pi_generator.py      — Generates/customizes PIs for the department
  agents/co_generator.py      — Generates NBA-compliant COs from syllabus
  agents/co_validator.py      — Validates CO quality (Bloom's, verb rules)
  agents/mapping_validator.py — Validates CO-PO mapping (NBA rules)
  core/schemas.py             — All Pydantic data models
  core/state.py               — AgentState — shared memory across all agents
  core/default_pis.py         — Department-specific PI template definitions
  core/orchestrator.py        — CLI-based orchestrator (legacy workflow)
  server.py                   — FastAPI server with all REST API endpoints

Frontend (React):
  src/pages/Mapping.jsx       — CO-PO and PI matrix UI, manual edit, save
  src/pages/CourseOutcomes.jsx— CO generation UI, feedback, manual edit
  src/pages/Setup.jsx         — Course setup, department, vision/mission upload
  src/pages/SubjectWorkspace.jsx — Main workspace orchestrating all phases

